If these things are s0, we may very readily compute the amount of blood and come to some conclusion on its circular motion. If, for instance, in phle- botomy, one were to let the blood flow with its usual

' force and rate for a half hour, there is no doubt but

that the greater part of it would be drained off, practically emptying not only arteries but also the great veins, and that fainting and syncope would follow. It is reasonable to assume that as great an amount of blood as is lost in this half hour’s time, passed from the great veins through the heart to the aorta.
